s places in England named with Middle English <i>stoke</i> (Old English <i>stoc</i>). The exact sense of the word is not clear, but it seems to have originally meant ‘place’ and was chiefly used for settlements dependent on a nearby estate center. Compare   Stoker  .","variant of   Stock  ."]},{"name":"Stoakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Stokes  ."]},{"name":"Stukes","meanings":["English: variant of   Stokes  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Stokes was born about 1390, in Kent, England as the daughter of Simon Stokes. She had at least 1 son and 4 daughters with William Lynne. She died after 1417."},"et":{"about 1390–after 1417":"umbes 1390–pärast 1417","1390–1417":"1390–1417","1384–1421":"1384–1421","1407–1474":"1407–1474","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1418–1486":"1418–1486","1418–1490":"1418–1490","–Female":"Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1384":"1384","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","Abt 1415":"umbes 1415","1415":"1415","about 1418":"umbes 1418","after 1417":"pärast 1417","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1486":"1486","1474":"1474","1407":"1407","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buc